 **AWS monitoring & logging setup from scratch** for EC2 / compute infrastructure.Here's your full setup guide for AWS EC2 monitoring and logging from scratch.

---

## Step 1 — Attach an IAM role to your EC2 instance

Your instance needs permissions to push data to CloudWatch. Create a role with these managed policies and attach it to each EC2 instance:

- `CloudWatchAgentServerPolicy` — lets the agent publish metrics and logs
- `AmazonSSMReadOnlyAccess` — lets the agent read its config from SSM Parameter Store (recommended)

---

## Step 2 — Install the CloudWatch Agent

SSH into each instance and run:

```bash
# Amazon Linux 2 / AL2023
sudo yum install -y amazon-cloudwatch-agent

# Ubuntu / Debian
wget https://s3.amazonaws.com/amazoncloudwatch-agent/ubuntu/amd64/latest/amazon-cloudwatch-agent.deb
sudo dpkg -i amazon-cloudwatch-agent.deb
```

---

## Step 3 — Configure the agent

Use the wizard to generate a config (or write one manually):

```bash
sudo /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-config-wizard
```

A minimal JSON config covering the most useful metrics and logs:

```json
{
  "metrics": {
    "namespace": "MyApp/EC2",
    "metrics_collected": {
      "cpu":    { "measurement": ["cpu_usage_idle", "cpu_usage_user"], "metrics_collection_interval": 60 },
      "mem":    { "measurement": ["mem_used_percent"], "metrics_collection_interval": 60 },
      "disk":   { "measurement": ["disk_used_percent"], "resources": ["/"], "metrics_collection_interval": 60 }
    }
  },
  "logs": {
    "logs_collected": {
      "files": {
        "collect_list": [
          { "file_path": "/var/log/syslog",       "log_group_name": "/ec2/syslog",   "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}" },
          { "file_path": "/var/log/app/app.log",  "log_group_name": "/ec2/app",      "log_stream_name": "{instance_id}" }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Store this in SSM Parameter Store (recommended):

```bash
aws ssm put-parameter \
  --name "/cloudwatch-agent/config" \
  --type "String" \
  --value file://config.json
```

Start the agent:

```bash
sudo /opt/aws/amazon-cloudwatch-agent/bin/amazon-cloudwatch-agent-ctl \
  -a fetch-config -m ec2 \
  -s -c ssm:/cloudwatch-agent/config
```

---

## Step 4 — Enable CloudTrail

CloudTrail captures every AWS API call (who did what, when).

```bash
aws cloudtrail create-trail \
  --name my-trail \
  --s3-bucket-name my-cloudtrail-bucket \
  --is-multi-region-trail

aws cloudtrail start-logging --name my-trail
```

Send CloudTrail logs to CloudWatch Logs for querying:

```bash
aws cloudtrail update-trail \
  --name my-trail \
  --cloud-watch-logs-log-group-arn arn:aws:logs:REGION:ACCOUNT:log-group:/cloudtrail/events:* \
  --cloud-watch-logs-role-arn arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT:role/CloudTrailRole
```

---

## Step 5 — Create CloudWatch Alarms

Set up alarms that trigger SNS notifications:

```bash
# CPU > 80% for 2 consecutive minutes
aws cloudwatch put-metric-alarm \
  --alarm-name "HighCPU" \
  --metric-name cpu_usage_user \
  --namespace MyApp/EC2 \
  --statistic Average \
  --period 60 \
  --evaluation-periods 2 \
  --threshold 80 \
  --comparison-operator GreaterThanThreshold \
  --alarm-actions arn:aws:sns:REGION:ACCOUNT:my-alerts-topic

# Disk > 85%
aws cloudwatch put-metric-alarm \
  --alarm-name "HighDiskUsage" \
  --metric-name disk_used_percent \
  --namespace MyApp/EC2 \
  --statistic Average \
  --period 300 \
  --evaluation-periods 1 \
  --threshold 85 \
  --comparison-operator GreaterThanThreshold \
  --alarm-actions arn:aws:sns:REGION:ACCOUNT:my-alerts-topic
```

---

## Step 6 — Set log retention policies

By default, CloudWatch log groups never expire and cost money indefinitely. Set a retention policy on each group:

```bash
aws logs put-retention-policy \
  --log-group-name /ec2/app \
  --retention-in-days 30
```

Typical values: 7 days (dev), 30 days (prod), 90–365 days (compliance).

---

## Key metrics to watch from day one

| What | Metric | Threshold |
|---|---|---|
| CPU | `cpu_usage_user` | Alert > 80% |
| Memory | `mem_used_percent` | Alert > 85% |
| Disk | `disk_used_percent` | Alert > 85% |
| Network errors | `net_err_in` / `net_err_out` | Any sustained non-zero |
| Status checks | `StatusCheckFailed` | Any failure |

