Here's a complete **GitHub Actions → AWS EKS automated deployment pipeline** from scratch.Here's everything you need to wire this up end to end.

---

## Step 1 — Prerequisites

Make sure you have these in place before writing any workflow:

- An EKS cluster running (`eksctl` or Terraform)
- An ECR repository for your Docker image
- An IAM user or OIDC role for GitHub Actions with these policies:
  - `AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryPowerUser`
  - `eks:DescribeCluster`, `eks:UpdateKubeconfig`

Store these as GitHub repository secrets:

| Secret | Value |
|---|---|
| `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | IAM key |
| `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | IAM secret |
| `AWS_REGION` | e.g. `ap-south-1` |
| `ECR_REGISTRY` | e.g. `123456789.dkr.ecr.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com` |
| `EKS_CLUSTER_NAME` | your cluster name |

> Using OIDC (recommended): you can skip long-lived keys entirely by federating GitHub as an OIDC provider and using `aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials` with a role ARN instead.

---

## Step 2 — The GitHub Actions workflow

Create `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`:

```yaml
name: Build and deploy to EKS

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

env:
  IMAGE_NAME: my-app
  K8S_NAMESPACE: production

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - name: Run tests
        run: |
          npm ci
          npm test

  build-and-push:
    needs: test
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    outputs:
      image-tag: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tag }}
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Configure AWS credentials
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
        with:
          aws-access-key-id: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID }}
          aws-secret-access-key: ${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY }}
          aws-region: ${{ secrets.AWS_REGION }}

      - name: Login to ECR
        uses: aws-actions/amazon-ecr-login@v2

      - name: Set image tag
        id: meta
        run: echo "tag=${{ secrets.ECR_REGISTRY }}/${{ env.IMAGE_NAME }}:${{ github.sha }}" >> $GITHUB_OUTPUT

      - name: Build and push
        run: |
          docker build -t ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tag }} .
          docker push ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tag }}

      - name: Scan image (Trivy)
        uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@master
        with:
          image-ref: ${{ steps.meta.outputs.tag }}
          severity: HIGH,CRITICAL
          exit-code: 1   # fail the job on critical CVEs

  deploy:
    needs: build-and-push
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    environment: production   # enables manual approval gate if configured
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Configure AWS credentials
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
        with:
          aws-access-key-id: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID }}
          aws-secret-access-key: ${{ secrets.AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY }}
          aws-region: ${{ secrets.AWS_REGION }}

      - name: Update kubeconfig
        run: |
          aws eks update-kubeconfig \
            --name ${{ secrets.EKS_CLUSTER_NAME }} \
            --region ${{ secrets.AWS_REGION }}

      - name: Deploy with Helm
        run: |
          helm upgrade --install my-app ./helm/my-app \
            --namespace ${{ env.K8S_NAMESPACE }} \
            --set image.tag=${{ github.sha }} \
            --set image.repository=${{ secrets.ECR_REGISTRY }}/my-app \
            --atomic \
            --timeout 5m
```

 rollback trigger — if the rollout fails or pods don't become ready within the timeout, Helm rolls back to the previous release automatically.

---

## Step 3 — Kubernetes manifests (if not using Helm)

If you prefer raw manifests over Helm, use `kustomize` with an image override:

```yaml
# k8s/deployment.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
  namespace: production
spec:
  replicas: 3
  strategy:
    type: RollingUpdate
    rollingUpdate:
      maxSurge: 1
      maxUnavailable: 0       # zero-downtime rolling deploy
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-app
          image: PLACEHOLDER   # replaced by kustomize at deploy time
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8080
          readinessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /health
              port: 8080
            initialDelaySeconds: 10
            periodSeconds: 5
```

Then in the deploy step replace the Helm command with:

```bash
cd k8s
kustomize edit set image my-app=${{ steps.meta.outputs.tag }}
kubectl apply -k .
kubectl rollout status deployment/my-app -n production --timeout=5m
```

---

## Step 4 — IAM with OIDC (recommended over long-lived keys)

This avoids storing AWS keys as secrets entirely:

```bash
# One-time setup: create OIDC provider for GitHub
eksctl utils associate-iam-oidc-provider \
  --cluster my-cluster --approve

# Create the role (replace YOUR_GITHUB_ORG/YOUR_REPO)
aws iam create-role --role-name GitHubActionsEKS \
  --assume-role-policy-document '{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [{
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": { "Federated": "arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT:oidc-provider/token.actions.githubusercontent.com" },
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
      "Condition": {
        "StringLike": { "token.actions.githubusercontent.com:sub": "repo:YOUR_GITHUB_ORG/YOUR_REPO:*" }
      }
    }]
  }'
```

Then in the workflow, swap the credentials step to:

```yaml
- uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v4
  with:
    role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::ACCOUNT:role/GitHubActionsEKS
    aws-region: ${{ secrets.AWS_REGION }}
```

And add `permissions: id-token: write` at the job level.

---

## Key things to get right

| Concern | How it's handled |
|---|---|
| Zero-downtime deploys | `maxUnavailable: 0` in RollingUpdate |
| Automatic rollback | `helm upgrade --atomic` or `kubectl rollout undo` |
| Image immutability | Tag images with `github.sha`, never `latest` |
| Security scanning | Trivy in CI blocks deploys with critical CVEs |
| Secrets | GitHub encrypted secrets or OIDC (no long-lived keys) |
| Manual approval | GitHub Environments with required reviewers |

